SIMPLE: spiral
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spiral
<hw>Spi"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>spiral</ets>. See <er>Spire</er> a winding line.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Winding or circling round a center or pole and gradually receding
from it; <as>as, the <ex>spiral</ex> curve of a watch
spring</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Winding round a cylinder or imaginary axis, and at
the same time rising or advancing forward; winding like the thread of a
screw; helical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a spiral;
like a spiral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Spiral gear</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Spiral
wheel</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a gear resembling in
general a spur gear, but having its teeth cut at an angle with its axis,
or so that they form small portions of screws or spirals.</cd> --
<col><b>Spiral gearing</b></col>, <cd>a kind of gearing sometimes used
in light machinery, in which spiral gears, instead of bevel gears, are
used to transmit motion between shafts that are not parallel.</cd> --
<col><b>Spiral operculum</b></col>, <cd>an operculum whih has spiral
lines of growth.</cd> -- <col><b>Spiral shell</b></col>, <cd>any shell
in which the whorls form a spiral or helix.</cd> -- <col><b>Spiral
spring</b></col>. <cd>See the <xex>Note</xex> under <er>Spring</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 4.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spiral</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spiral
<hw>Spi"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>spirale</ets>. See <er>Spiral</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A plane curve, not reentrant,
described by a point, called the <xex>generatrix</xex>, moving along a
straight line according to a mathematical law, while the line is
revolving about a fixed point called the <xex>pole</xex>. Cf.
<er>Helix</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything which has a spiral form, as a spiral
shell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Equiangular spiral</b></col>,<cd>a plane curve which cuts
all its generatrices at the same angle. Same as <altname>Logarithmic
spiral</altname>, under <er>Logarithmic</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spiral of
Archimedes</b></col>, <cd>a spiral the law of which is that the
generatrix moves uniformly along the revolving line, which also moves
uniformly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spirality</ent>⟦br⟧
